üîπ New Point to Add
Unnecessary and Unused Dependencies Introduced by Arun Framework
Arun Framework defines and includes a set of JAR dependencies intended to support multiple use cases.
However, not all applications require all framework-provided dependencies.
As a result:
Applications inherit JARs that are not actually used
These JARs still appear in:
Dependency trees
Veracode and security scans
Runtime classpaths
Impact:
Increased attack surface due to unused libraries
Additional security findings for code paths not used by the application
Larger dependency trees, making troubleshooting and upgrades more complex
Additionally:
Applications already manage multiple third-party JARs outside Arun Framework
Managing Spring and Gradle dependencies directly would simply extend an existing, proven responsibility rather than introduce a new one
